:"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (Glasgow): nickname from Middle English, Older Scots, and Old French <i>simple</i> ‘simple, straightforward, humble’ (from Latin <i>simplus</i>). The Scottish name was taken to Ulster in the 17th century, and a Scottish family of this name held the hereditary post of Sheriff of Renfrewshire from the 13th century.","English: variant of   Sample  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Sample","meanings":["English (northeastern): of Norman origin, a habitational name from any of numerous places in northern France named Saint-Paul or Saint-Pol, for example in Pas-de-Calais, Nord, and Finistère, so called from the dedication of their churches to Saint Paul."]}]},{"name":"Ellinor","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Corrupted from Eleanor,"],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705212,"age":10,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Ellinor Semple was born about 1610, in England, United Kingdom. She married Richard Hughes on 1 December 1634, in Llanllugan, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died about 1635, in Shropshire, England, at the age of 27."},"et":{"Abt 1610–abt 1635":"umbes 1610–umbes 1635","1610–1687":"1610–1687","1635–1635":"1635–1635","1635–1723":"1635–1723","1636–Male":"1636–Surnud","1610–1635":"1610–1635